1. Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)\
RBAC is a system where access permissions are assigned based on a user\'92s role within an organization. This approach ensures security, reduces administrative overhead, and aligns with business workflows.\
Key Principles of RBAC:\
	1.	Role Hierarchy:\
	\'95	Organize roles in a hierarchical structure.\
	\'95	Higher roles inherit permissions from lower roles.\
	\'95	Example: Super Admin > Admin > Manager > Employee > Viewer.\
	2.	Permission Assignment:\
	\'95	Assign permissions to roles, not users.\
	\'95	Users inherit permissions by being assigned roles.\
	3.	Granular Access Control:\
	\'95	Define fine-grained permissions for actions, such as:\
	\'95	Read, Write, Update, Delete (CRUD).\
	\'95	Module-specific actions (e.g., access to Reports, Invoices).\
	4.	Separation of Duties:\
	\'95	Prevent role conflicts (e.g., one user cannot approve and audit the same transaction).\
	5.	Role Management:\
	\'95	Support dynamic role creation.\
	\'95	Allow for role-specific dashboards and workflows.\
	6.	Need-to-Know Basis:\
	\'95	Ensure users see only the data they are authorized to view.\
RBAC Implementation Steps:\
	1.	Define Roles and Permissions:\
	\'95	Identify key roles in the system (e.g., Super Admin, Vendor, Client).\
	\'95	Map roles to permissions (e.g., View Dashboard, Manage Users).\
	2.	Assign Roles to Users:\
	\'95	Use databases (e.g., PostgreSQL, Firestore) to map users to roles.\
	3.	Authorization Middleware:\
	\'95	Implement middleware to check permissions before granting access.\
	4.	Audit and Logs:\
	\'95	Maintain logs for access requests and changes to roles/permissions.\
	5.	Dynamic Updates:\
	\'95	Enable role/permission updates without affecting system uptime.\
    2. Modular Architecture\
\
Modular architecture ensures that the application is broken into independent, self-contained modules. Each module focuses on a specific functionality, improving scalability, reusability, and maintainability.\
\
Key Principles of Modular Architecture:\
	1.	Separation of Concerns:\
	\'95	Each module handles a distinct responsibility (e.g., User Management, Payments, Analytics).\
	2.	Independent Development:\
	\'95	Modules can be developed, tested, and deployed independently.\
	3.	Reusability:\
	\'95	Common functionalities (e.g., Authentication, Notifications) are abstracted into shared modules.\
	4.	Loose Coupling:\
	\'95	Minimize dependencies between modules.\
	\'95	Use APIs or message queues for inter-module communication.\
	5.	Scalability:\
	\'95	Add new modules without affecting existing functionality.\
\
Industry-Standard Module Build-Up:\
	1.	Core Modules:\
	\'95	Authentication: Manage user login, registration, and token-based sessions.\
	\'95	RBAC: Assign roles and permissions dynamically.\
	\'95	User Management: Manage user profiles, roles, and permissions.\
	2.	Business Modules:\
	\'95	Tailored to the business domain, such as:\
	\'95	CRM: Manage leads, clients, and campaigns.\
	\'95	Inventory: Track stock and supply chain.\
	\'95	Payments: Handle invoicing and payment processing.\
	3.	Shared Modules:\
	\'95	Notifications: Handle email, SMS, and push notifications.\
	\'95	Logging: Capture and store logs for debugging and auditing.\
	\'95	Analytics: Provide dashboards and reports.\
	4.	Front-End Modules:\
	\'95	Component-based architecture (e.g., React or Angular).\
	\'95	Role-specific dashboards and UI elements.\
	5.	API Layer:\
	\'95	Standardized REST or GraphQL endpoints for communication.\
